body:
The guard-condition simplification in `simplifyActionWithGuard` replaces uses of the guard expression with a boolean constant inside action regions. When a boolean `fsm.variable` is used directly as a guard condition, this replacement was applied erroneously to the first operand of `fsm.update`, which is the variable being assigned to (not a value to be folded). This produced invalid IR like `fsm.update %true, %false` instead of `fsm.update %flag, %false`.

The fix adds a check in the `replaceUsesWithIf` predicate to skip operand 0 of `UpdateOp`, which is always the assignment target.


Example of the bug:

```mlir
// test: guard-constant folding replaces the variable operand of
// fsm.update with a constant when a boolean fsm.variable is used directly
// as a guard condition.
// Expected: fsm.update %flag_var, <new_value>
// Bug:      fsm.update %true_const, <new_value>  (variable ref replaced!)
// Run: circt-opt --convert-core-to-fsm guard_fold_bug_test.mlir
hw.module @guard_fold_bug(in %clk : !seq.clock, in %rst : i1, out out : i1) {
    %false = hw.constant false
    %true = hw.constant true
    %state = seq.compreg name "state" %next_state, %clk reset %rst, %false : i1
    // Boolean variable whose value is used directly as a guard condition.
    // The guard-constant folder will try to replace it
    // with hw.constant true inside the action region but including the
    // left operand of the fsm.update that targets this variable.
    %flag = seq.compreg name "flag" %next_flag, %clk reset %rst, %false : i1
    %state_is_0 = comb.xor %state, %true : i1
    %go_to_1 = comb.and %flag, %state_is_0 : i1
    %not_flag = comb.xor %flag, %true : i1
    %stay_at_0 = comb.and %state_is_0, %not_flag : i1
    %next_state = comb.mux %stay_at_0, %false, %go_to_1 : i1
    %next_flag = comb.xor %flag, %true : i1
    hw.output %flag : i1
}
```

```mlir
module {
  fsm.machine @guard_fold_bug() -> i1 attributes {initialState = "state_0"} {
    %flag = fsm.variable "flag" {initValue = false} : i1
    fsm.state @state_0 output {
      fsm.output %flag : i1
    } transitions {
      fsm.transition @state_1 guard {
        fsm.return %flag
      } action {
        %true = hw.constant true
        %false = hw.constant false
        fsm.update %true, %false : i1
      }
      fsm.transition @state_0 guard {
        %true = hw.constant true
        %0 = comb.xor %flag, %true : i1
        fsm.return %0
      } action {
        %false = hw.constant false
        %true = hw.constant true
        fsm.update %false, %true : i1
      }
    }
    fsm.state @state_1 output {
      fsm.output %flag : i1
    } transitions {
      fsm.transition @state_0 guard {
        %true = hw.constant true
        fsm.return %true
      } action {
        %true = hw.constant true
        %0 = comb.xor %flag, %true : i1
        fsm.update %flag, %0 : i1
      }
    }
  }
}
```

Note how `fsm.update %false, %true` is clearly erroneous,
because the left-hand side of an assignment
can't be a constant literal.
